aa(lp74
VSo, what threatens to happen with this unfolding apocalypse
p75
aVis the collapse of global social organization.
p76
aVNow, first let me remind you how much work it took to get us where we are,
p77
aVto be on the brink of true global social organization.
p78
aVOriginally, you had the most complex societies, the hunter-gatherer village.
p79
aVStonehenge is the remnant of a chiefdom,
p80
aVwhich is what you get with the invention of agriculture: multi-village polity
p81
aVwith centralized rule.
p82
aVWith the invention of writing, you start getting cities. This is blurry. I kind of like that
p83
aVbecause it makes it look like a one-celled organism and reminds you
p84
aVhow many levels organic organization has already moved through
p85
aVto get to this point. And then you get to, you know, you get empires.
p86
aa(lp87
VI want to stress, you know, social organization can transcend political bounds.
p88
aVThis is the Silk Road connecting the Chinese Empire and the Roman Empire.
p89
aVSo you had social complexity spanning the whole continent,
p90
aVeven if no polity did similarly. Today, you've got nation states.
p91
aVPoint is: there's obviously collaboration and organization going on
p92
aVbeyond national bounds.
p93
aVThis is actually just a picture of the earth at night,
p94
aVand I'm just putting it up because I think it's pretty.
p95
aVDoes kind of convey the sense that this is an integrated system.
